# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: model-based-design
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] In computer science, **automatic programming** is a type of computer programming in which some mechanism generates a computer program, to allow human programmers to write the code at a higher abstraction level.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] There has been little agreement on the precise definition of automatic programming, mostly because its meaning has changed over time.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] David Parnas, tracing the history of "automatic programming" in published research, noted that in the 1940s it described automation of the manual process of punching paper tape.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] Later it referred to translation of high-level programming languages like Fortran and ALGOL.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] One of the earliest programs identifiable as a compiler is named Autocode.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] Program synthesis is one type of automatic programming where a procedure is created from scratch, based on mathematical requirements.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] Mildred Koss, an early UNIVAC programmer, explains: "Writing machine code involved several tedious steps—breaking down a process into discrete instructions, assigning specific memory locations to all the commands, and managing the I/O buffers.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] After following these steps to implement mathematical routines, a sub-routine library, and sorting programs, our task was to look at the larger programming process.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] We needed to understand how we might reuse tested code and have the machine help in programming.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] As we programmed, we examined the process and tried to think of ways to abstract these steps to incorporate them into higher-level language.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] The goal is to improve programmer productivity.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] It is often related to code-reuse topics such as component-based software engineering.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] Modern programming languages are well supported by tools like Json4Swift (Swift) and Json2Kotlin (Kotlin).
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] These application generators supported COBOL inserts and overrides.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] A macro processor, such as the C preprocessor, which replaces patterns in source code according to relatively simple rules, is a simple form of source-code generator.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] Source-to-source code generation tools also exist.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] Large language models such as ChatGPT are capable of generating a program's source code from a description of the program given in a natural language.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] Many relational database management systems (RDBMS) provide a function that will export the content of the database as SQL data definition queries, which may then be executed to re-import the tables and their data, or migrate them to another RDBMS.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] Some languages use *annotations* to generate source code and inject it.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] For example, this is done in Java and Kotlin using annotations, for example the Project Lombok library which runs at compile time with an annotation processor.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] There has been a C++ proposal to add token sequence injection using compile-time reflective programming (reflection).
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] A low-code development platform (LCDP) is software that provides an environment programmers use to create application software through graphical user interfaces and configuration instead of traditional computer programming.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] Vibe coding is a software development practice assisted by artificial intelligence (AI) where the software developer describes a project or task in a prompt to a large language model (LLM) which generates source code automatically.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] Vibe coding may involve accepting AI-generated code without thorough review of the output, instead relying on results and follow-up prompts to guide changes.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] The term was coined in February 2025 by computer scientist Andrej Karpathy, a co-founder of OpenAI and former AI leader at Tesla.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] Merriam-Webster listed the term in March 2025 as a "slang & trending" expression.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] It was named the *Collins English Dictionary* Word of the Year for 2025.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] Advocates of vibe coding say that it allows even amateur programmers to produce software without the extensive training and skills required for software engineering.
[src:model-based-design/automatic-programming] Critics point out a lack of accountability, maintainability, and an increased risk of introducing security vulnerabilities in the resulting software.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] A precise and stable characteristic feature is that no or not all functions of embedded software are initiated/controlled via a human interface, but through machine-interfaces instead.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Manufacturers build embedded software into the electronics of cars, telephones, modems, robots, appliances, toys, security systems, pacemakers, televisions and set-top boxes, and digital watches, for example.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] This software can be very simple, such as lighting controls running on an 8-bit microcontroller with a few kilobytes of memory with the suitable level of processing complexity determined with a Probably Approximately Correct Computation framework (a methodology based on randomized algorithms).
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] However, embedded software can become very sophisticated in applications such as routers, optical network elements, airplanes, missiles, and process control systems.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Unlike standard computers that generally use operating systems such as macOS, Windows or Linux, embedded software may use no operating system.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] When they do use one, a wide variety of operating systems can be chosen from, typically a real-time operating system.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Code for embedded software is typically written in C or C++, but various high-level programming languages, such as C#, Java, Python and JavaScript, are now also in common use to target microcontrollers and embedded systems.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Assembly languages are often used too, especially in booting and interrupt handling.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Ada is used in some military and aviation projects.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Most consumers are familiar with application software that provide functionality on a computer.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] However embedded software is often less visible, but no less complicated.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Unlike application software, embedded software has fixed hardware requirements and capabilities, and addition of third-party hardware or software is strictly controlled.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Embedded software needs to include all needed device drivers at manufacturing time, and the device drivers are written for the various hardware devices.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] The software is highly dependent on the CPU and specific chips chosen.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Most embedded software engineers have at least a passing knowledge of reading schematics, and reading data sheets for components to determine usage of registers and communication system.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Conversion between decimal, hexadecimal and binary is useful as well as using bit manipulation.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Web applications are often used for managing hardware, although XML files and other output may be passed to a computer for display.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] File systems with folders are typically used, however SQL databases are often absent.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Software development requires use of a cross compiler, which runs on a computer but produces executable code for the target device.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Debugging requires use of an in-circuit emulator, and debugging hardware such as JTAG or SWD debuggers.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Software developers often have access to the complete kernel (OS) source code.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Size of the storage memory and RAM can vary significantly.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Some systems run in 16 KB of Flash and 4 KB of RAM with a CPU operating at 8 MHz, other systems can rival contemporary computers.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] These space requirements lead to more work being done in C or embedded C++, instead of C++.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Interpreted languages like BASIC (while e.g.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Parallax Propeller can use compiled BASIC) and Java (Java ME Embedded 8.3 is available for e.g.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] ARM Cortex-M4, Cortex-M7 microcontrollers and older ARM11 used in Raspberry Pi and Intel Galileo Gen.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] 2) are not commonly used; while an implementation of the interpreted Python 3 language – MicroPython – is however available expressly for microcontroller use, e.g.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] 32-bit ARM-based (such as BBC micro:bit) and 16-bit PIC microcontrollers.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Communications between processors and between one processor and other components are essential.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Besides direct memory addressing, hardware level common protocols include I²C, SPI, serial ports, 1-Wires, Ethernets, and USB.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Communications protocols designed for use in embedded systems are available as closed source from companies including InterNiche Technologies and CMX Systems.
[src:model-based-design/embedded-software] Open-source protocols stem from uIP, lwip, and others.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] Model-based design provides an efficient approach for establishing a common framework for communication throughout the design process while supporting the development cycle (V-model).
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] 4. integrating all these phases by deploying the controller.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] The model-based design is significantly different from traditional design methodology.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] Rather than using complex structures and extensive software code, designers can use Model-based design to define plant models with advanced functional characteristics using continuous-time and discrete-time building blocks.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] These built models used with simulation tools can lead to rapid prototyping, software testing, and verification.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] Not only is the testing and verification process enhanced, but also, in some cases, hardware-in-the-loop simulation can be used with the new design paradigm to perform testing of dynamic effects on the system more quickly and much more efficiently than with traditional design methodology.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] As early as the 1920s two aspects of engineering, control theory and control systems, converged to make large-scale integrated systems possible.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] In those early days controls systems were commonly used in the industrial environment.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] Large process facilities started using process controllers for regulating continuous variables such as temperature, pressure, and flow rate.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] Electrical relays built into ladder-like networks were one of the first discrete control devices to automate an entire manufacturing process.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] Control systems gained momentum, primarily in the automotive and aerospace sectors.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] In the 1950s and 1960s, the push to space generated interest in embedded control systems.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] Engineers constructed control systems such as engine control units and flight simulators, that could be part of the end product.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] By the end of the twentieth century, embedded control systems were ubiquitous, as even major household consumer appliances such as washing machines and air conditioners contained complex and advanced control algorithms, making them much more "intelligent".
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] In 1969, the first computer-based controllers were introduced.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] These early programmable logic controllers (PLC) mimicked the operations of already available discrete control technologies that used the out-dated relay ladders.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] The advent of PC technology brought a drastic shift in the process and discrete control market.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] An off-the-shelf desktop loaded with adequate hardware and software can run an entire process unit, and execute complex and established PID algorithms or work as a Distributed Control System (DCS).
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] The mathematical model conceived in step 1 is used to identify dynamic characteristics of the plant model.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] A controller can then be synthesized based on these characteristics.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] Offline simulation and real-time simulation.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] The time response of the dynamic system to complex, time-varying inputs is investigated.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] This is done by simulating a simple LTI (Linear Time-Invariant) model, or by simulating a non-linear model of the plant with the controller.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] Simulation allows specification, requirements, and modeling errors to be found immediately, rather than later in the design effort.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] Real-time simulation can be done by automatically generating code for the controller developed in step 2.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] This code can be deployed to a special real-time prototyping computer that can run the code and control the operation of the plant.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] If a plant prototype is not available, or testing on the prototype is dangerous or expensive, code can be automatically generated from the plant model.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] This code can be deployed to the special real-time computer that can be connected to the target processor with running controller code.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] Thus a controller can be tested in real-time against a real-time plant model.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] Ideally this is done via code generation from the controller developed in step 2.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] It is unlikely that the controller will work on the actual system as well as it did in simulation, so an iterative debugging process is carried out by analyzing results on the actual target and updating the controller model.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] Model-based design tools allow all these iterative steps to be performed in a unified visual environment.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] The disadvantages of model-based design are fairly well understood this late in development lifecycle of the product and development.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] While Model-based design has the ability to simulate test scenarios and interpret simulations well, in real world production environments, it is often not suitable.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] Over reliance on a given toolchain can lead to significant rework and possibly compromise entire engineering approaches.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] While it's suitable for bench work, the choice to use this for a production system should be made very carefully.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] Because of the limitations of graphical tools, design engineers previously relied heavily on text-based programming and mathematical models.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] However, developing these models was time-consuming, and highly prone to error.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] In addition, debugging text-based programs is a tedious process, requiring much trial and error before a final fault-free model could be created, especially since mathematical models undergo unseen changes during the translation through the various design stages.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] Graphical modeling tools aim to improve these aspects of design.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] These tools provide a very generic and unified graphical modeling environment, and they reduce the complexity of model designs by breaking them into hierarchies of individual design blocks.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] Designers can thus achieve multiple levels of model fidelity by simply substituting one block element with another.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] Graphical models also help engineers to conceptualize the entire system and simplify the process of transporting the model from one stage to another in the design process.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] Boeing's simulator EASY5 was among the first modeling tools to be provided with a graphical user interface, together with AMESim, a multi-domain, multi-level platform based on the Bond Graph theory.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] This was soon followed by tool like 20-sim and Dymola, which allowed models to be composed of physical components like masses, springs, resistors, etc.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-design] These were later followed by many other modern tools such as Simulink and LabVIEW.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-systems-engineering] Unlike document-based approaches where system specifications are scattered across numerous text documents, spreadsheets, and diagrams that can become inconsistent over time, MBSE centralizes information in interconnected models that automatically maintain relationships between system elements.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-systems-engineering] These models serve as the authoritative source of truth for system design, enabling automated verification of requirements, real-time impact analysis of proposed changes, and generation of consistent documentation from a single source.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-systems-engineering] This approach significantly reduces errors from manual synchronization, improves traceability between requirements and implementation, and facilitates earlier detection of design flaws through simulation and analysis.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-systems-engineering] The MBSE approach has been widely adopted across industries dealing with complex systems development, including aerospace, defense, rail, automotive, and manufacturing.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-systems-engineering] By enabling consistent system representation across disciplines and development phases, MBSE helps organizations manage complexity, reduce development risks, improve quality, and enhance collaboration among multidisciplinary teams.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-systems-engineering] The first known prominent public usage of the term "Model-Based Systems Engineering" is a book by A.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-systems-engineering] The standardization of SysML in 2006 resulted in widespread modeling tool support for it and associated MBSE processes that emphasized SysML as their *lingua franca*.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-systems-engineering] In September 2007, the MBSE approach was further generalized and popularized when INCOSE introduced its "MBSE 2020 Vision", which was not restricted to SysML, and supported other competitive modeling language standards, such as AP233, HLA, and Modelica.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-systems-engineering] As of 2014, the scope of MBSE started to cover more Modeling and Simulation topics, in an attempt to bridge the gap between system model specifications and related system software simulations.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-systems-engineering] As a consequence, the term "modeling and simulation-based systems engineering" has also been increasingly associated along with MBSE.
[src:model-based-design/model-based-systems-engineering] According to the INCOSE *SEBoK* (*Systems Engineering Book of Knowledge*) MBSE may be considered a "subset of digital engineering".
[src:model-based-design/model-based-systems-engineering] INCOSE hosts an annual meeting on MBSE, as well as MBSE working groups.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] A **simulation** is an imitative representation of a process or system that could exist in the real world.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] In this broad sense, simulation can often be used interchangeably with model.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Sometimes a clear distinction between the two terms is made, in which simulations require the use of models; the model represents the key characteristics or behaviors of the selected system or process, whereas the simulation represents the evolution of the model over time.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Another way to distinguish between the terms is to define simulation as experimentation with the help of a model.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] This definition includes time-independent simulations.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Often, computers are used to execute the simulation.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Simulation is used in many contexts, such as simulation of technology for performance tuning or optimizing, safety engineering, testing, training, education, and video games.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Simulation is also used with scientific modelling of natural systems or human systems to gain insight into their functioning, as in economics.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Simulation can be used to show the eventual real effects of alternative conditions and courses of action.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Simulation is also used when the real system cannot be engaged, because it may not be accessible, or it may be dangerous or unacceptable to engage, or it is being designed but not yet built, or it may simply not exist.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Procedures and protocols for model verification and validation are an ongoing field of academic study, refinement, research and development in simulations technology or practice, particularly in the work of computer simulation.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Historically, simulations used in different fields developed largely independently, but 20th-century studies of systems theory and cybernetics combined with the spreading use of computers across all those fields have led to some unification and a more systematic view of the concept.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] A *stand-alone simulation* is a simulation running on a single workstation by itself.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] A **distributed simulation** is one which uses more than one computer simultaneously, to guarantee access from/to different resources (e.g. multi-users operating different systems, or distributed data sets); a classical example is Distributed Interactive Simulation (DIS).
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] A *synthetic environment* is a computer simulation that can be included in human-in-the-loop simulations.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Data simulation creates artificial data to replicate the behavior of real-world data.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] The artificial data is generated using computer models or programs based on specific rules, patterns, or characteristics.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] This type of data is designed to imitate the operations of real systems, processes, or behaviors, enabling researchers and analysts to study and test scenarios without directly observing or collecting information from the real world.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] A computer simulation (or "sim") is an attempt to model a real-life or hypothetical situation on a computer so that it can be studied to see how the system works.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] By changing variables in the simulation, predictions may be made about the behaviour of the system.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] It is a tool to virtually investigate the behaviour of the system under study.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Computer simulation has become a useful part of modeling many natural systems in physics, chemistry and biology, and human systems in economics and social science (e.g., computational sociology) as well as in engineering to gain insight into the operation of those systems.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] A good example of the usefulness of using computers to simulate can be found in the field of network traffic simulation.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] In such simulations, the model behaviour will change each simulation according to the set of initial parameters assumed for the environment.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Traditionally, the formal modeling of systems has been via a mathematical model, which attempts to find analytical solutions enabling the prediction of the behaviour of the system from a set of parameters and initial conditions.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Computer simulation is often used as an adjunct to, or substitution for, modeling systems for which simple closed form analytic solutions are not possible.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] There are many different types of computer simulation, the common feature they all share is the attempt to generate a sample of representative scenarios for a model in which a complete enumeration of all possible states would be prohibitive or impossible.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Several software packages exist for running computer-based simulation modeling (e.g.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Monte Carlo simulation, stochastic modeling, multimethod modeling) that makes all the modeling almost effortless.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Modern usage of the term "computer simulation" may encompass virtually any computer-based representation.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] The computer simulates the subject machine.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Accordingly, in theoretical computer science the term *simulation* is a relation between state transition systems, useful in the study of operational semantics.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Less theoretically, an interesting application of computer simulation is to simulate computers using computers.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] For example, simulators have been used to debug a microprogram or sometimes commercial application programs, before the program is downloaded to the target machine.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Since the operation of the computer is simulated, all of the information about the computer's operation is directly available to the programmer, and the speed and execution of the simulation can be varied at will.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Simulators may also be used to interpret fault trees, or test VLSI logic designs before they are constructed.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Symbolic simulation uses variables to stand for unknown values.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] In the field of optimization, simulations of physical processes are often used in conjunction with evolutionary computation to optimize control strategies.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Simulation is extensively used for educational purposes.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] It is used for cases where it is prohibitively expensive or simply too dangerous to allow trainees to use the real equipment in the real world.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] In such situations they will spend time learning valuable lessons in a "safe" virtual environment yet living a lifelike experience (or at least it is the goal).
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Often the convenience is to permit mistakes during training for a safety-critical system.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Simulations in education are somewhat like training simulations.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] The term 'microworld' is used to refer to educational simulations which model some abstract concept rather than simulating a realistic object or environment, or in some cases model a real-world environment in a simplistic way so as to help a learner develop an understanding of the key concepts.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Normally, a user can create some sort of construction within the microworld that will behave in a way consistent with the concepts being modeled.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Seymour Papert was one of the first to advocate the value of microworlds, and the Logo programming environment developed by Papert is one of the most well-known microworlds.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Project management simulation is increasingly used to train students and professionals in the art and science of project management.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Using simulation for project management training improves learning retention and enhances the learning process.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] In recent years, there has been increasing use of social simulations for staff training in aid and development agencies.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] The Carana simulation, for example, was first developed by the United Nations Development Programme, and is now used in a very revised form by the World Bank for training staff to deal with fragile and conflict-affected countries.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Military uses for simulation often involve aircraft or armoured fighting vehicles, but can also target small arms and other weapon systems training.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Specifically, virtual firearms ranges have become the norm in most military training processes and there is a significant amount of data to suggest this is a useful tool for armed professionals.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] A **virtual simulation** is a category of simulation that uses simulation equipment to create a **simulated world** for the user.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Virtual simulations allow users to interact with a virtual world.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Virtual worlds operate on platforms of integrated software and hardware components.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] In this manner, the system can accept input from the user (e.g., body tracking, voice/sound recognition, physical controllers) and produce output to the user (e.g., visual display, aural display, haptic display) .
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Virtual simulations use the aforementioned modes of interaction to produce a sense of immersion for the user.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] There is a wide variety of input hardware available to accept user input for virtual simulations.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Research in future input systems holds a great deal of promise for virtual simulations.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Systems such as brain–computer interfaces (BCIs) offer the ability to further increase the level of immersion for virtual simulation users.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Lee, Keinrath, Scherer, Bischof, Pfurtscheller proved that naïve subjects could be trained to use a BCI to navigate a virtual apartment with relative ease.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Using the BCI, the authors found that subjects were able to freely navigate the virtual environment with relatively minimal effort.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] It is possible that these types of systems will become standard input modalities in future virtual simulation systems.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] There is a wide variety of output hardware available to deliver stimuli to users in virtual simulations.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Many medical simulators involve a computer connected to a plastic simulation of the relevant anatomy.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Sophisticated simulators of this type employ a life-size mannequin that responds to injected drugs and can be programmed to create simulations of life-threatening emergencies.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] In other simulations, visual components of the procedure are reproduced by computer graphics techniques, while touch-based components are reproduced by haptic feedback devices combined with physical simulation routines computed in response to the user's actions.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Medical simulations of this sort will often use 3D CT or MRI scans of patient data to enhance realism.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Some medical simulations are developed to be widely distributed (such as web-enabled simulations and procedural simulations that can be viewed via standard web browsers) and can be interacted with using standard computer interfaces, such as the keyboard and mouse.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] An important medical application of a simulator—although, perhaps, denoting a slightly different meaning of *simulator*—is the use of a placebo drug, a formulation that simulates the active drug in trials of drug efficacy.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Patient safety is a concern in the medical industry.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Patients have been known to suffer injuries and even death due to management error, and lack of using best standards of care and training.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Simulation is being used to study patient safety, as well as train medical professionals.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Studying patient safety and safety interventions in healthcare is challenging, because there is a lack of experimental control (i.e., patient complexity, system/process variances) to see if an intervention made a meaningful difference (Groves & Manges, 2017).
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] An example of innovative simulation to study patient safety is from nursing research.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] (2016) used a high-fidelity simulation to examine nursing safety-oriented behaviors during times such as change-of-shift report.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] However, the value of simulation interventions to translating to clinical practice are is still debatable.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] As Nishisaki states, "there is good evidence that simulation training improves provider and team self-efficacy and competence on manikins.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] There is also good evidence that procedural simulation improves actual operational performance in clinical settings." However, there is a need to have improved evidence to show that crew resource management training through simulation.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] One of the largest challenges is showing that team simulation improves team operational performance at the bedside.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Although evidence that simulation-based training actually improves patient outcome has been slow to accrue, today the ability of simulation to provide hands-on experience that translates to the operating room is no longer in doubt.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] One of the largest factors that might impact the ability to have training impact the work of practitioners at the bedside is the ability to empower frontline staff (Stewart, Manges, Ward, 2015).
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Another example of an attempt to improve patient safety through the use of simulations training is patient care to deliver just-in-time service or/and just-in-place.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] This training consists of 20 minutes of simulated training just before workers report to shift.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] One study found that just in time training improved the transition to the bedside.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] The conclusion as reported in Nishisaki (2008) work, was that the simulation training improved resident participation in real cases; but did not sacrifice the quality of service.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] It could be therefore hypothesized that by increasing the number of highly trained residents through the use of simulation training, that the simulation training does, in fact, increase patient safety.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] The first medical simulators were simple models of human patients.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Since antiquity, these representations in clay and stone were used to demonstrate clinical features of disease states and their effects on humans.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Models have been found in many cultures and continents.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] These models have been used in some cultures (e.g., Chinese culture) as a "diagnostic" instrument, allowing women to consult male physicians while maintaining social laws of modesty.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Models are used today to help students learn the anatomy of the musculoskeletal system and organ systems.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] The need for a "uniform mechanism to educate, evaluate, and certify simulation instructors for the health care profession" was recognized by McGaghie et al. in their critical review of simulation-based medical education research.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] In 2012 the SSH piloted two new certifications to provide recognition to educators in an effort to meet this need.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Active models that attempt to reproduce living anatomy or physiology are recent developments.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] The famous "Harvey" mannequin was developed at the University of Miami and is able to recreate many of the physical findings of the cardiology examination, including palpation, auscultation, and electrocardiography.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] More recently, interactive models have been developed that respond to actions taken by a student or physician.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Until recently, these simulations were two dimensional computer programs that acted more like a textbook than a patient.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Computer simulations have the advantage of allowing a student to make judgments, and also to make errors.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] The process of iterative learning through assessment, evaluation, decision making, and error correction creates a much stronger learning environment than passive instruction.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Simulators have been proposed as an ideal tool for assessment of students for clinical skills.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] For patients, "cybertherapy" can be used for sessions simulating traumatic experiences, from fear of heights to social anxiety.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Programmed patients and simulated clinical situations, including mock disaster drills, have been used extensively for education and evaluation.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] These "lifelike" simulations are expensive, and lack reproducibility.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] A fully functional "3Di" simulator would be the most specific tool available for teaching and measurement of clinical skills.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Gaming platforms have been applied to create these virtual medical environments to create an interactive method for learning and application of information in a clinical context.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Immersive disease state simulations allow a doctor or HCP to experience what a disease actually feels like.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Using sensors and transducers, symptomatic effects can be delivered to a participant, allowing them to experience the patient’s disease state.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Such a simulator meets the goals of an objective and standardized examination for clinical competence.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] This system is superior to examinations that use "standard patients" because it permits the quantitative measurement of competence, as well as reproducing the same objective findings.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] The first simulation game may have been created as early as 1947 by Thomas T.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] This was a straightforward game that simulated a missile being fired at a target.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] The curve of the missile and its speed could be adjusted using several knobs.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] In 1958, a computer game called *Tennis for Two* was created by Willy Higginbotham which simulated a tennis game between two players who could both play at the same time using hand controls and was displayed on an oscilloscope.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] This was one of the first electronic video games to use a graphical display.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Computer-generated imagery was used in the film to simulate objects as early as 1972 in *A Computer Animated Hand*, parts of which were shown on the big screen in the 1976 film *Futureworld*.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] This was followed by the "targeting computer" that young Skywalker turns off in the 1977 film *Star Wars*.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] The film *Tron* (1982) was the first film to use computer-generated imagery for more than a couple of minutes.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Advances in technology in the 1980s caused 3D simulation to become more widely used and it began to appear in movies and in computer-based games such as Atari's *Battlezone* (1980) and Acornsoft's *Elite* (1984), one of the first wire-frame 3D graphics games for home computers.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Advances in technology in the 1980s made the computer more affordable and more capable than they were in previous decades, which facilitated the rise of computer such as the Xbox gaming.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] The first video game consoles released in the 1970s and early 1980s fell prey to the industry crash in 1983, but in 1985, Nintendo released the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES) which became one of the best selling consoles in video game history.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] In the 1990s, computer games became widely popular with the release of such game as *The Sims* and *Command & Conquer* and the still increasing power of desktop computers.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Today, computer simulation games such as *World of Warcraft* are played by millions of people around the world.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] In 1993, the film *Jurassic Park* became the first popular film to use computer-generated graphics extensively, integrating the simulated dinosaurs almost seamlessly into live action scenes.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] This event transformed the film industry; in 1995, the film *Toy Story* was the first film to use only computer-generated images and by the new millennium computer generated graphics were the leading choice for special effects in films.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] The advent of virtual cinematography in the early 2000s has led to an explosion of movies that would have been impossible to shoot without it.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Classic examples are the digital look-alikes of Neo, Smith and other characters in the *Matrix* sequels and the extensive use of physically impossible camera runs in *The Lord of the Rings* trilogy.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Computer-generated imagery is "the application of the field of 3D computer graphics to special effects".
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] This technology is used for visual effects because they are high in quality, controllable, and can create effects that would not be feasible using any other technology either because of cost, resources or safety.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Computer-generated graphics can be seen in many live-action movies today, especially those of the action genre.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Further, computer-generated imagery has almost completely supplanted hand-drawn animation in children's movies which are increasingly computer-generated only.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Examples of movies that use computer-generated imagery include *Finding Nemo*, *300* and *Iron Man*.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Simulation games, as opposed to other genres of video and computer games, represent or simulate an environment accurately.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Moreover, they represent the interactions between the playable characters and the environment realistically.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] These kinds of games are usually more complex in terms of gameplay.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Simulation games have become incredibly popular among people of all ages.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Popular simulation games include *SimCity* and *Tiger Woods PGA Tour*.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] There are also flight simulator and driving simulator games.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Simulators have been used for entertainment since the Link Trainer in the 1930s.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] The first modern simulator ride to open at a theme park was Disney's Star Tours in 1987 soon followed by Universal's The Funtastic World of Hanna-Barbera in 1990 which was the first ride to be done entirely with computer graphics.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Simulator rides are the progeny of military training simulators and commercial simulators, but they are different in a fundamental way.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] While military training simulators react realistically to the input of the trainee in real time, ride simulators only feel like they move realistically and move according to prerecorded motion scripts.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] One of the first simulator rides, Star Tours, which cost $32 million, used a hydraulic motion based cabin.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] The movement was programmed by a joystick.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Today's simulator rides, such as The Amazing Adventures of Spider-Man include elements to increase the amount of immersion experienced by the riders such as: 3D imagery, physical effects (spraying water or producing scents), and movement through an environment.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p01] Another important goal of simulation in manufacturing systems is to quantify system performance.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] An automobile simulator provides an opportunity to reproduce the characteristics of real vehicles in a virtual environment.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] It replicates the external factors and conditions with which a vehicle interacts enabling a driver to feel as if they are sitting in the cab of their own vehicle.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Scenarios and events are replicated with sufficient reality to ensure that drivers become fully immersed in the experience rather than simply viewing it as an educational experience.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] The simulator provides a constructive experience for the novice driver and enables more complex exercises to be undertaken by the more mature driver.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] For novice drivers, truck simulators provide an opportunity to begin their career by applying best practice.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] For mature drivers, simulation provides the ability to enhance good driving or to detect poor practice and to suggest the necessary steps for remedial action.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] For companies, it provides an opportunity to educate staff in the driving skills that achieve reduced maintenance costs, improved productivity and, most importantly, to ensure the safety of their actions in all possible situations.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] A **biomechanics simulator** is a simulation platform for creating dynamic mechanical models built from combinations of rigid and deformable bodies, joints, constraints, and various force actuators.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] It is specialized for creating biomechanical models of human anatomical structures, with the intention to study their function and eventually assist in the design and planning of medical treatment.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] A biomechanics simulator is used to analyze walking dynamics, study sports performance, simulate surgical procedures, analyze joint loads, design medical devices, and animate human and animal movement.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] A neuromechanical simulator combines biomechanical and biologically realistic neural network simulation.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] It allows the user to test hypotheses about the neural basis of behavior in a physically accurate 3D virtual environment.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] A city simulator can be a city-building game but can also be a tool used by urban planners to understand how cities are likely to evolve in response to various policy decisions.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] AnyLogic is an example of modern, large-scale urban simulators designed for use by urban planners.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] City simulators are generally agent-based simulations with explicit representations for land use and transportation.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] UrbanSim and LEAM are examples of large-scale urban simulation models that are used by metropolitan planning agencies and military bases for land use and transportation planning.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Several Christmas-themed simulations exist, many of which are centered around Santa Claus.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] An example of these simulations are websites which claim to allow the user to track Santa Claus.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Another example of these simulations are websites that claim to allow the user to email or send messages to Santa Claus.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Websites such as emailSanta.com or Santa's former page on the now-defunct Windows Live Spaces by Microsoft use automated programs or scripts to generate personalized replies claimed to be from Santa himself based on user input.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Modern satellite communications systems (SATCOM) are often large and complex with many interacting parts and elements.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] In addition, the need for broadband connectivity on a moving vehicle has increased dramatically in the past few years for both commercial and military applications.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] To accurately predict and deliver high quality of service, SATCOM system designers have to factor in terrain as well as atmospheric and meteorological conditions in their planning.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] To deal with such complexity, system designers and operators increasingly turn towards computer models of their systems to simulate real-world operating conditions and gain insights into usability and requirements prior to final product sign-off.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Modeling improves the understanding of the system by enabling the SATCOM system designer or planner to simulate real-world performance by injecting the models with multiple hypothetical atmospheric and environmental conditions.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Simulation is often used in the training of civilian and military personnel.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] This usually occurs when it is prohibitively expensive or simply too dangerous to allow trainees to use the real equipment in the real world.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] In such situations, they will spend time learning valuable lessons in a "safe" virtual environment yet living a lifelike experience (or at least it is the goal).
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Simulation solutions are being increasingly integrated with computer-aided solutions and processes (computer-aided design or CAD, computer-aided manufacturing or CAM, computer-aided engineering or CAE, etc.).
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] The use of simulation throughout the product lifecycle, especially at the earlier concept and design stages, has the potential of providing substantial benefits.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] These benefits range from direct cost issues such as reduced prototyping and shorter time-to-market to better performing products and higher margins.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] However, for some companies, simulation has not provided the expected benefits.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] The successful use of simulation, early in the lifecycle, has been largely driven by increased integration of simulation tools with the entire set of CAD, CAM and product-lifecycle management solutions.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Simulation solutions can now function across the extended enterprise in a multi-CAD environment, and include solutions for managing simulation data and processes and ensuring that simulation results are made part of the product lifecycle history.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Simulation training has become a method for preparing people for disasters.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Simulations can replicate emergency situations and track how learners respond thanks to a lifelike experience.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Disaster preparedness simulations can involve training on how to handle terrorism attacks, natural disasters, pandemic outbreaks, or other life-threatening emergencies.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] One organization that has used simulation training for disaster preparedness is CADE (Center for Advancement of Distance Education).
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] CADE has used a video game to prepare emergency workers for multiple types of attacks.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] The Emergency Simulation Program (ESP) at the British Columbia Institute of Technology (BCIT), Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada is another example of an organization that uses simulation to train for emergency situations.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] At the University of Québec in Chicoutimi, a research team at the outdoor research and expertise laboratory (Laboratoire d'Expertise et de Recherche en Plein Air – LERPA) specializes in using wilderness backcountry accident simulations to verify emergency response coordination.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Instructionally, the benefits of emergency training through simulations are that learner performance can be tracked through the system.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] This allows the developer to make adjustments as necessary or alert the educator on topics that may require additional attention.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Other advantages are that the learner can be guided or trained on how to respond appropriately before continuing to the next emergency segment—this is an aspect that may not be available in the live environment.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Some emergency training simulators also allow for immediate feedback, while other simulations may provide a summary and instruct the learner to engage in the learning topic again.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] In a live-emergency situation, emergency responders do not have time to waste.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Simulation-training in this environment provides an opportunity for learners to gather as much information as they can and practice their knowledge in a safe environment.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] They can make mistakes without risk of endangering lives and be given the opportunity to correct their errors to prepare for the real-life emergency.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Simulation is an important feature in engineering systems or any system that involves many processes.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] For example, in electrical engineering, delay lines may be used to simulate propagation delay and phase shift caused by an actual transmission line.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Similarly, dummy loads may be used to simulate impedance without simulating propagation and is used in situations where propagation is unwanted.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] A simulator may imitate only a few of the operations and functions of the unit it simulates.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Most engineering simulations entail mathematical modeling and computer-assisted investigation.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] There are many cases, however, where mathematical modeling is not reliable.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Simulation of fluid dynamics problems often require both mathematical and physical simulations.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] In these cases the physical models require dynamic similitude.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Physical and chemical simulations have also direct realistic uses, rather than research uses; in chemical engineering, for example, process simulations are used to give the process parameters immediately used for operating chemical plants, such as oil refineries.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Simulators are also used for plant operator training.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] It is called Operator Training Simulator (OTS) and has been widely adopted by many industries from chemical to oil&gas and to the power industry.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] This created a safe and realistic virtual environment to train board operators and engineers.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Mimic is capable of providing high fidelity dynamic models of nearly all chemical plants for operator training and control system testing.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Software tools typically calculate biomechanical properties including individual muscle forces, joint forces and moments.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Most of these tools employ standard ergonomic evaluation methods such as the NIOSH lifting equation and Rapid Upper Limb Assessment (RULA).
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Some simulations also analyze physiological measures including metabolism, energy expenditure, and fatigue limits Cycle time studies, design and process validation, user comfort, reachability, and line of sight are other human-factors that may be examined in ergonomic simulation packages.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Modeling and simulation of a task can be performed by manually manipulating the virtual human in the simulated environment.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Some ergonomics simulation software permits interactive, real-time simulation and evaluation through actual human input via motion capture technologies.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] However, motion capture for ergonomics requires expensive equipment and the creation of props to represent the environment or product.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Some applications of ergonomic simulation in include analysis of solid waste collection, disaster management tasks, interactive gaming, automotive assembly line, virtual prototyping of rehabilitation aids, and aerospace product design.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Ford engineers use ergonomics simulation software to perform virtual product design reviews.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Using engineering data, the simulations assist evaluation of assembly ergonomics.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] The company uses Siemen's Jack and Jill ergonomics simulation software in improving worker safety and efficiency, without the need to build expensive prototypes.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] In finance, computer simulations are often used for scenario planning.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Risk-adjusted net present value, for example, is computed from well-defined but not always known (or fixed) inputs.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] By imitating the performance of the project under evaluation, simulation can provide a distribution of NPV over a range of discount rates and other variables.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Simulations are also often used to test a financial theory or the ability of a financial model.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Simulations are frequently used in financial training to engage participants in experiencing various historical as well as fictional situations.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] There are stock market simulations, portfolio simulations, risk management simulations or models and forex simulations.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Such simulations are typically based on stochastic asset models.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Using these simulations in a training program allows for the application of theory into a something akin to real life.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] As with other industries, the use of simulations can be technology or case-study driven.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Flight simulation is mainly used to train pilots outside of the aircraft.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] In comparison to training in flight, simulation-based training allows for practicing maneuvers or situations that may be impractical (or even dangerous) to perform in the aircraft while keeping the pilot and instructor in a relatively low-risk environment on the ground.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] For example, electrical system failures, instrument failures, hydraulic system failures, and even flight control failures can be simulated without risk to the crew or equipment.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Instructors can also provide students with a higher concentration of training tasks in a given period of time than is usually possible in the aircraft.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Flight simulation also provides an economic advantage over training in an actual aircraft.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Once fuel, maintenance, and insurance costs are taken into account, the operating costs of an FSTD are usually substantially lower than the operating costs of the simulated aircraft.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] For some large transport category airplanes, the operating costs may be several times lower for the FSTD than the actual aircraft.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Another advantage is reduced environmental impact, as simulators don't contribute directly to carbon or noise emissions.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] There also exist "engineering flight simulators" which are a key element of the aircraft design process.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Many benefits that come from a lower number of test flights like cost and safety improvements are described above, but there are some unique advantages.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Having a simulator available allows for faster design iteration cycle or using more test equipment than could be fit into a real aircraft.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Bearing resemblance to flight simulators, a **marine simulator** is meant for training of ship personnel.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Simulators like these are mostly used within maritime colleges, training institutions, and navies.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] They often consist of a replication of a ships' bridge, with the operating console(s), and a number of screens on which the virtual surroundings are projected.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Military simulations, also known informally as war games, are models in which theories of warfare can be tested and refined without the need for actual hostilities.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] They exist in many different forms, with varying degrees of realism.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] In recent times, their scope has widened to include not only military but also political and social factors (for example, the Nationlab series of strategic exercises in Latin America).
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] While many governments make use of simulation, both individually and collaboratively, little is known about the model's specifics outside professional circles.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Network and distributed systems have been extensively simulated in other to understand the impact of new protocols and algorithms before their deployment in the actual systems.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] The simulation can focus on different levels (physical layer, network layer, application layer), and evaluate different metrics (network bandwidth, resource consumption, service time, dropped packets, system availability).
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Simulation techniques have also been applied to payment and securities settlement systems.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Among the main users are central banks, which are generally responsible for the oversight of market infrastructure and are entitled to contribute to the smooth functioning of payment systems.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Central banks have been using payment system simulations to evaluate things such as the adequacy or sufficiency of liquidity available ( in the form of account balances and intraday credit limits) to participants (mainly banks) to allow efficient settlement of payments.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] The need for liquidity is also dependent on the availability and the type of netting procedures in the systems, thus some of the studies have a focus on system comparisons.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Another application is to evaluate risks related to events such as communication network breakdowns or the inability of participants to send payments (e.g. in case of possible bank failure).
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] This kind of analysis falls under the concepts of stress testing or scenario analysis.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] A common way to conduct these simulations is to replicate the settlement logics of the real payment or securities settlement systems under analysis and then use real observed payment data.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] In case of system comparison or system development, naturally, also the other settlement logics need to be implemented.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] To perform stress testing and scenario analysis, the observed data needs to be altered, e.g. some payments delayed or removed.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] To analyze the levels of liquidity, initial liquidity levels are varied.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] System comparisons (benchmarking) or evaluations of new netting algorithms or rules are performed by running simulations with a fixed set of data and varying only the system setups.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] An inference is usually done by comparing the benchmark simulation results to the results of altered simulation setups by comparing indicators such as unsettled transactions or settlement delays.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Project management simulation is simulation used for project management training and analysis.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] It is often used as a training simulation for project managers.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] In other cases, it is used for what-if analysis and for supporting decision-making in real projects.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Frequently the simulation is conducted using software tools.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] A robotics simulator is used to create embedded applications for a specific (or not) robot without being dependent on the 'real' robot.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] In some cases, these applications can be transferred to the real robot (or rebuilt) without modifications.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Robotics simulators allow reproducing situations that cannot be 'created' in the real world because of cost, time, or the 'uniqueness' of a resource.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] A simulator also allows fast robot prototyping.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Many robot simulators feature physics engines to simulate a robot's dynamics.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Such simulations can help predict the impact of how improvements in methods might impact variability, cost, labor time, and the number of transactions at various stages in the process.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] A full-featured computerized process simulator can be used to depict such models, as can simpler educational demonstrations using spreadsheet software, pennies being transferred between cups based on the roll of a die, or dipping into a tub of colored beads with a scoop.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] In sports, computer simulations are often done to predict the outcome of events and the performance of individual sportspeople.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] They attempt to recreate the event through models built from statistics.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] The increase in technology has allowed anyone with knowledge of programming the ability to run simulations of their models.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] The simulations are built from a series of mathematical algorithms, or models, and can vary with accuracy.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Accuscore, which is licensed by companies such as ESPN, is a well-known simulation program for all major sports.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] It offers a detailed analysis of games through simulated betting lines, projected point totals and overall probabilities.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] With the increased interest in fantasy sports simulation models that predict individual player performance have gained popularity.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Companies like What If Sports and StatFox specialize in not only using their simulations for predicting game results but how well individual players will do as well.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Many people use models to determine whom to start in their fantasy leagues.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Another way simulations are helping the sports field is in the use of biomechanics.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Models are derived and simulations are run from data received from sensors attached to athletes and video equipment.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Sports biomechanics aided by simulation models answer questions regarding training techniques such as the effect of fatigue on throwing performance (height of throw) and biomechanical factors of the upper limbs (reactive strength index; hand contact time).
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Computer simulations allow their users to take models which before were too complex to run, and give them answers.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Simulations have proven to be some of the best insights into both play performance and team predictability.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Simulation was used at Kennedy Space Center (KSC) to train and certify Space Shuttle engineers during simulated launch countdown operations.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] The Space Shuttle engineering community would participate in a launch countdown integrated simulation before each Shuttle flight.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] This simulation is a virtual simulation where real people interact with simulated Space Shuttle vehicle and Ground Support Equipment (GSE) hardware.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] The Shuttle Final Countdown Phase Simulation, also known as S0044, involved countdown processes that would integrate many of the Space Shuttle vehicle and GSE systems.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Some of the Shuttle systems integrated in the simulation are the main propulsion system, RS-25, solid rocket boosters, ground liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen, external tank, flight controls, navigation, and avionics.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] The Shuttle Final Countdown Phase Simulation took place at the Kennedy Space Center Launch Control Center firing rooms.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] The firing room used during the simulation is the same control room where real launch countdown operations are executed.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] As a result, equipment used for real launch countdown operations is engaged.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] The Space Shuttle vehicle hardware and related GSE hardware is simulated by mathematical models (written in Shuttle Ground Operations Simulator (SGOS) modeling language) that behave and react like real hardware.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] During the Shuttle Final Countdown Phase Simulation, engineers command and control hardware via real application software executing in the control consoles – just as if they were commanding real vehicle hardware.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] However, these real software applications do not interface with real Shuttle hardware during simulations.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Instead, the applications interface with mathematical model representations of the vehicle and GSE hardware.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Consequently, the simulations bypass sensitive and even dangerous mechanisms while providing engineering measurements detailing how the hardware would have reacted.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Since these math models interact with the command and control application software, models and simulations are also used to debug and verify the functionality of application software.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] The only true way to test GNSS receivers (commonly known as Sat-Nav's in the commercial world) is by using an RF Constellation Simulator.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] A receiver that may, for example, be used on an aircraft, can be tested under dynamic conditions without the need to take it on a real flight.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] The test conditions can be repeated exactly, and there is full control over all the test parameters. this is not possible in the 'real-world' using the actual signals.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] For testing receivers that will use the new Galileo (satellite navigation) there is no alternative, as the real signals do not yet exist.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Predicting weather conditions by extrapolating/interpolating previous data is one of the real use of simulation.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Most of the weather forecasts use this information published by Weather bureaus.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] This kind of simulations helps in predicting and forewarning about extreme weather conditions like the path of an active hurricane/cyclone.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Numerical weather prediction for forecasting involves complicated numeric computer models to predict weather accurately by taking many parameters into account.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Strategy games—both traditional and modern—may be viewed as simulations of abstracted decision-making for the purpose of training military and political leaders (see History of Go for an example of such a tradition, or Kriegsspiel for a more recent example).
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Many other video games are simulators of some kind.
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] Such games can simulate various aspects of reality, from business, to government, to construction, to piloting vehicles (see above).
[src:model-based-design/simulation-p02] However, the connection between simulation and dissembling later faded out and is now only of linguistic interest.
[src:model-based-design/systems-modeling] A common type of systems modeling is function modeling, with specific techniques such as the Functional Flow Block Diagram and IDEF0.
[src:model-based-design/systems-modeling] These models can be extended using functional decomposition, and can be linked to requirements models for further systems partition.
[src:model-based-design/systems-modeling] Contrasting the functional modeling, another type of systems modeling is architectural modeling which uses the systems architecture to conceptually model the structure, behavior, and more views of a system.
[src:model-based-design/systems-modeling] The Business Process Modeling Notation (BPMN), a graphical representation for specifying business processes in a workflow, can also be considered to be a systems modeling language.
[src:model-based-design/systems-modeling] In business and IT development the term "systems modeling" has multiple meanings.
[src:model-based-design/systems-modeling] As a field of study systems modeling has emerged with the development of system theory and systems sciences.
[src:model-based-design/systems-modeling] As a type of modeling systems modeling is based on systems thinking and the systems approach.
[src:model-based-design/systems-modeling] In "Methodology for Creating Business Knowledge" (1997) Arbnor and Bjerke the systems approach (systems modeling) was considered to be one of the three basic methodological approaches for gaining business knowledge, beside the analytical approach and the actor's approach (agent based modeling).
[src:model-based-design/systems-modeling] The function model originates in the 1950s, after in the first half of the 20th century other types of management diagrams had already been developed.
[src:model-based-design/systems-modeling] The first known Gantt chart was developed in 1896 by Karol Adamiecki, who called it a *harmonogram*.
[src:model-based-design/systems-modeling] One of the first well defined function models, was the Functional Flow Block Diagram (FFBD) developed by the defense-related TRW Incorporated in the 1950s.
[src:model-based-design/systems-modeling] In the 1960s it was exploited by the NASA to visualize the time sequence of events in a space systems and flight missions.
[src:model-based-design/systems-modeling] It is further widely used in classical systems engineering to show the order of execution of system functions.
[src:model-based-design/systems-modeling] Since we may be called upon to evaluate different computers or to find alternative ways of organizing current systems it is necessary to have some means of precisely stating a data processing problem independently of mechanization.
[src:model-based-design/systems-modeling] They aimed for a precise and abstract way of specifying the informational and time characteristics of a data processing problem, and wanted to create a notation that should enable the analyst to organize the problem around any piece of hardware.
[src:model-based-design/systems-modeling] Their efforts was not so much focused on independent systems analysis, but on creating abstract specification and invariant basis for designing different alternative implementations using different hardware components.
[src:model-based-design/systems-modeling] A next step in IS modeling was taken by CODASYL, an IT industry consortium formed in 1959, who essentially aimed at the same thing as Young and Kent: the development of "a proper structure for machine independent problem definition language, at the system level of data processing".
[src:model-based-design/systems-modeling] This led to the development of a specific IS information algebra.
[src:model-based-design/systems-modeling] And all other specific types of systems modeling, such as form example complex systems modeling, dynamical systems modeling, and critical systems modeling.
